# HEADLESS ACCESSIBILITY PRIMITIVES RULESET
**(WCAG 2.2 AA – Behavior & Semantics Only + WAI-ARIA 1.2 + Safe 1.3 Forward + React Aria Tier Edge Cases)**

**0. GLOBAL ENFORCEMENT**  
1. All generated primitives MUST follow this document exactly.  
2. Any violation = immediate rejection and full regeneration.  
3. WCAG 2.2 AA behavior and semantics are mandatory.  
4. The library MUST NOT add any CSS, colors, spacing, layout, or design.  
5. Only semantics, state, keyboard logic, focus management, and interaction are allowed.

**1. SEMANTIC GUARANTEES**  
1. Use native HTML elements first ("No ARIA is better than bad ARIA").  
2. ARIA only when native elements cannot do the job.  
3. Every interactive item MUST be focusable when enabled.  
4. Accessible name MUST come from visible text, aria-label, or aria-labelledby.  
5. Support aria-describedby, aria-errormessage, and aria-invalid.  
6. All ARIA MUST stay perfectly synced with React state at all times.  
7. Always add `data-state` attributes ("open" | "closed" | "active" | "inactive" etc.).

**2. KEYBOARD INTERACTION GUARANTEES**  
Follow **WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices Guide 1.2 exactly** for every widget.  
1. Tab and Shift+Tab in logical DOM order.  
2. Enter and Space for activation.  
3. Escape closes everything dismissible.  
4. Arrow keys for menus, tabs, radios, composites.  
5. Roving tabindex: only one tabindex="0" at a time.  
6. For 3+ items: Home, End, Page Up, Page Down where appropriate.  
7. Type-to-jump with letter keys for long lists.  
8. Skip disabled and hidden items.  
9. Never use positive tabindex values.  
10. For any widget: use the exact pattern from WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices Guide 1.2 section for that role.

**3. WAI-ARIA 1.3 FORWARD COMPATIBILITY (SAFE PRACTICES)**  
WAI-ARIA 1.3 is still a Working Draft. Base everything on stable APG 1.2.  
Safe to adopt immediately (without breaking 1.2 compatibility):  
• Prefer `aria-description` for short descriptions when appropriate.  
• Follow updated live-region timing and best practices (including hidden announcer, queue, and 200 ms delay for non-overlapping announcements).  
• Support `aria-details` (can reference multiple IDs).  
• Prepare for new roles (comment, suggestion, mark) but **do not use them yet** in production code.  
• `aria-braillelabel` and `aria-brailleroledescription` only if explicitly requested.  
All 1.3 features must remain optional and non-breaking.

**4. FOCUS MANAGEMENT GUARANTEES**  
For modals, popovers, dialogs, and menus:  
1. Move focus to the first focusable item on open.  
2. Trap focus inside the container.  
3. Return focus to the trigger on close (Escape or outside click).  
4. Never create keyboard traps.  
5. For portals: always use React Portal and handle focus after mount.  
6. Expose focus state via data attributes.  
7. Handle nested widgets by restoring focus to the correct parent on close.

**5. STATE & LIVE REGION GUARANTEES**  
1. State is internal or controlled via props.  
2. ARIA attributes update instantly with state.  
3. Use aria-live="polite" by default for status changes.  
4. Announcements must be concise (max ~10 words) and only convey changed values.  
5. For status primitives (Toast, Alert, etc.): add an OPTIONAL single hidden live-region announcer in the Provider (controlled by `useSmartAnnouncer` prop).  
6. Build smart contextual messages from props only (example: "Success: " + title or "Error: " + description).  
7. Use a queue + 200 ms delay so multiple announcements never overlap (optional – default off for zero delay).  
8. Hidden announcer must stay visually hidden (consumer provides sr-only styles) but fully accessible to screen readers.  
9. Visible toast content remains exactly as before – no changes required.

**6. DRAG AND DROP GUARANTEES**  
1. Always provide full keyboard alternative.  
2. Use arrow keys for reordering.  
3. Announce start, current position, and drop result.  
4. Do not use deprecated ARIA (no aria-grabbed).

**7. USER PREFERENCE GUARANTEES**  
1. Respect prefers-reduced-motion.  
2. Respect prefers-contrast and forced-colors mode.  
3. Never override user contrast or motion settings.

**8. INTERNATIONALIZATION & COMPOSABILITY**  
1. No hardcoded strings – all text via props.  
2. Full dir="rtl" support.  
3. Handle text expansion gracefully.  
4. Primitives must be nestable and composable without breaking ARIA or focus.  
5. Support i18n message formatting (optional formatter function in Provider for translated smart announcements).

**9. SERVER RENDERING GUARANTEES**  
1. Server-rendered HTML must match client HTML.  
2. No browser-only APIs during SSR.  
3. No focus management on the server.

**10. VIRTUALIZATION GUARANTEES**  
1. Focus position remains stable.  
2. Correct aria-posinset and aria-setsize.  
3. Keyboard navigation and type-to-search must continue to work.  
4. Proper position announcements in large lists.

**11. EXTRA SUPPORT**  
1. Expose refs, state, and helper utilities for testing.  
2. Include built-in support for keyboard and live-region testing (include queue and announcer helpers).  
3. Provide optional useAnnouncer hook for custom status components.

**12. COMPOUND COMPONENT REQUIREMENTS**  
Every multi-part primitive (Accordion, Tabs, etc.) MUST:  
• Use React Context with a Provider.  
• Properly forward refs.  
• Correctly wire aria-controls, aria-labelledby, aria-expanded.  
• Handle asChild on all sub-components safely.  
• Never assume sub-components exist without proper context.

**13. WHAT THE LIBRARY MUST NEVER DO**  
- Add any CSS or visual styles  
- Enforce target size or focus indicator thickness  
- Guarantee contrast or Lighthouse scores  
- Override consumer styles or preferences

**14. CONSUMER RESPONSIBILITIES**  
Clearly document that the consumer is responsible for:  
1. Visible focus indicators (2.4.7)  
2. Color contrast (1.4.3)  
3. Target size (2.5.8)  
4. Full page + real screen reader testing

**15. DEEP EDGE-CASE PROTECTION GUARANTEES (React Aria Tier)**  
1. Handle dynamic content changes without losing focus or breaking live regions.  
2. Auto-restore focus in nested dialogs, popovers, and portals.  
3. Fix known browser bugs (focus jumping in lists, VoiceOver double-announce, TalkBack swipe quirks) using safe workarounds.  
4. Support mobile touch + keyboard combos for all widgets.  
5. Keep announcements stable during fast re-renders.  
6. All fixes must be optional and tree-shakable.

**PRIORITY ORDER**  
1. WCAG 2.2 AA  
2. Native HTML first  
3. APG 1.2 (with safe 1.3 forward practices)  
4. Deep edge-case robustness  
5. Maximum consumer flexibility

**REJECTION CONDITION**  
Any code that breaks any rule above (especially missing Provider in compound components, incomplete APG 1.2 patterns, or incorrect ARIA) MUST be rejected and fully regenerated until it is perfect.

When generating or regenerating code, always append this line at the bottom of your response:
"Accessibility compliance: WCAG 2.2 AA semantics + APG 1.2 with safe WAI-ARIA 1.3 forward practices + React Aria tier edge-case protection."